  "prompt": "How does the form of government in Jamaica differs from the one in Italy?",
  "response": "Jamaica and Italy have different forms of government, reflecting their distinct political histories and structures.\n\n### Jamaica\n- **Type of Government**: Jamaica is a parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy. \n- **Monarch**: The head of state is the monarch of the United Kingdom, represented in Jamaica by the Governor-General.\n- **Prime Minister**: The head of government is the Prime Minister, who is the leader of the majority party in the House of Representatives.\n- **Legislature**: Jamaica has a bicameral legislature, consisting of the House of Representatives (lower house) and the Senate (upper house).\n- **Elections**: Members of the House of Representatives are elected by the public, while Senators are appointed.\n\n### Italy\n- **Type of Government**: Italy is a parliamentary republic.\n- **President**: The head of state is the President of the Republic, who has a more ceremonial role.\n- **Prime Minister**: The head of government is the Prime Minister, who is typically the leader of the majority party or coalition in Parliament.\n- **Legislature**: Italy also has a bicameral legislature, consisting of the Chamber of Deputies (lower house) and the Senate of the Republic (upper house).\n- **Elections**: Members of both houses are elected, with the Chamber of Deputies being elected directly by the public and the Senate having both elected and regional representatives.\n\n### Key Differences\n1. **Monarchy vs. Republic**: Jamaica recognizes a monarch as the head of state, while Italy is a republic without a monarchy.\n2. **Governor-General**: Jamaica has a Governor-General representing the monarch, whereas Italy does not have a similar institution.\n3. **Ceremonial Roles**: In Jamaica, the monarch (via the Governor-General) has a ceremonial role, while in Italy, the President plays a ceremonial role and has some political functions.\n4. **Political History**: Jamaica's colonial history influenced its constitutional monarchy, while Italy's political structure developed from a republican context following the fall of the monarchy in the mid-20th century.\n\nThese differences reflect the unique political and historical contexts of each country.",
